WEBVTT



00:00:00.210 --> 00:00:04.019
Welcome my friend to today's
lecture on money and banking.

00:00:04.470 --> 00:00:08.490
We're about to make the complicated,
ridiculously clear on this

00:00:08.495 --> 00:00:09.965
concept with this tutorial.

00:00:11.355 --> 00:00:12.885
Concept explanation.

00:00:13.245 --> 00:00:15.344
All right, let's get straight into it.

00:00:15.855 --> 00:00:20.625
Money and banking are the two big
pillars holding up any modern economy.

00:00:21.015 --> 00:00:25.064
If you want to work in banking, you
have to know the stuff inside out.

00:00:25.545 --> 00:00:26.745
So what is money?

00:00:27.654 --> 00:00:32.845
At its heart, money is simply anything
that is generally accepted as payment

00:00:32.845 --> 00:00:35.754
for goods and services or to repay debts.

00:00:36.175 --> 00:00:40.885
Before we had our lovely currency notes,
people were stuck with the barter system.

00:00:41.245 --> 00:00:45.385
Just imagine a farmer trading his
wheat for a carpenter's chair.

00:00:45.775 --> 00:00:47.605
It sounds simple, but it was.

00:00:47.660 --> 00:00:52.760
Terribly inefficient because of something
called the double coincidence of wants.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:54.260
What a mouthful, eh?

00:00:54.739 --> 00:00:58.879
It just means that both people
had to want exactly what the

00:00:58.879 --> 00:01:00.260
other person was offering.

00:01:00.650 --> 00:01:04.250
The farmer needs a chair, and
the carpenter must need wheat.

00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:08.090
If the carpenter wanted
shoes instead, well no deal.

00:01:08.509 --> 00:01:12.229
Money came in and solved this
massive headache by performing

00:01:12.229 --> 00:01:13.759
several key functions.

00:01:14.295 --> 00:01:16.605
First, it's a medium of exchange.

00:01:16.785 --> 00:01:19.335
It completely removes the need for barter.

00:01:19.725 --> 00:01:24.195
You can sell your goods for money and
then use that money to buy whatever you

00:01:24.195 --> 00:01:26.955
want whenever you want, so much simpler.

00:01:27.375 --> 00:01:29.535
Second, it's a unit of account.

00:01:29.865 --> 00:01:32.715
It gives us a common
measuring stick for value.

00:01:33.134 --> 00:01:35.595
Every single thing from a tiny pin.

00:01:35.670 --> 00:01:39.600
To a huge house can be priced
in money, making it super

00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:41.550
easy to compare their values.

00:01:42.030 --> 00:01:43.980
Third, it's a store of value.

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:48.480
This function allows people to save
their purchasing power for later.

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:52.620
Of course, its value can get eaten
away by our friendly neighborhood

00:01:52.620 --> 00:01:56.760
villain in inflation, but generally
it holds its value over time.

00:01:57.180 --> 00:02:00.180
And fourth, it's a standard
of deferred payment.

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:04.780
This fancy phrase means it allows
for future payments, which is the

00:02:04.780 --> 00:02:07.240
backbone of all borrowing and lending.

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:10.389
All debts are usually set in money terms.

00:02:10.930 --> 00:02:12.970
Now let's talk about banking.

00:02:13.300 --> 00:02:17.530
Banking is the business of accepting
and looking after the money owned by

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:22.570
people and companies, and then lending
that money out to help the economy grow.

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:27.010
Think of banks as the middlemen
or financial intermediaries.

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:29.460
Connecting those who have extra money.

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:34.500
The savers with those who need it, the
borrowers, commercial banks are the

00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:36.630
ones you and I deal with every day.

00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:40.740
They take our deposits like
in savings, current or fixed

00:02:40.740 --> 00:02:42.090
accounts, and give out loans.

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:45.130
For personal use business or housing.

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:50.110
They also offer other handy services
like sending money, providing locker

00:02:50.110 --> 00:02:52.510
facilities, and of course credit cards.

00:02:52.810 --> 00:02:58.600
Examples you see everywhere are State Bank
of India, HDFC Bank, and I-C-I-C-I bank.

00:02:59.110 --> 00:03:02.440
Then we have the big boss,
the Central Bank, which in

00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:04.360
India is our very own reserve.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:05.950
Bank of India or RBI.

00:03:06.645 --> 00:03:11.565
Every country has one, and its job is
to regulate the entire banking system

00:03:11.685 --> 00:03:13.605
and control the supply of money.

00:03:14.025 --> 00:03:16.875
The RBI has some very important functions.

00:03:17.204 --> 00:03:21.644
It is the monetary authority,
meaning it creates implements, and

00:03:21.644 --> 00:03:23.894
keeps an eye on the monetary policy.

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:28.880
It's also the regulator and supervisor
of the financial system setting

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:33.410
the main rules for how banks should
operate it is the manager of Foreign

00:03:33.410 --> 00:03:38.810
Exchange handling the Foreign Exchange
Management Act of FEMA from 1999.

00:03:39.230 --> 00:03:43.370
It is the issuer of currency,
the only body that can issue and

00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:45.500
exchange currency notes and coins.

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:50.450
It also plays a developmental role
helping financial institutions and

00:03:50.450 --> 00:03:55.400
markets grow, and it's the banker to the
government managing the bank accounts

00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:57.590
of both central and state governments.

00:03:57.710 --> 00:04:01.850
Finally, it's the banker to banks
holding the bank accounts of all

00:04:01.850 --> 00:04:04.460
scheduled banks, key concepts.

00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:07.610
Now for a few key ideas, you must.

00:04:07.610 --> 00:04:08.054
No.

00:04:08.415 --> 00:04:09.885
First is inflation.

00:04:10.274 --> 00:04:14.084
This is when there's a sustained
increase in the general price level

00:04:14.084 --> 00:04:16.274
of goods and services over time.

00:04:16.784 --> 00:04:20.414
In simple words, your money
buys less than it did before.

00:04:20.834 --> 00:04:24.914
That a hundred rupe note just
doesn't stretch as far as it used to.

00:04:25.545 --> 00:04:27.375
Next is monetary policy.

00:04:27.770 --> 00:04:32.150
This is the process the Central bank
uses to control the supply of money.

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:37.610
It often targets an inflation rate or
an interest rate to make sure prices are

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:40.040
stable and people trust the currency.

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:42.830
Finally, there's credit creation.

00:04:43.219 --> 00:04:47.510
This is the almost magical process
where commercial banks create new

00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:49.610
money just by giving out loans.

00:04:50.090 --> 00:04:53.870
When a bank lends you money, it
creates a deposit in your account,

00:04:54.020 --> 00:04:55.640
which effectively increases the.

00:04:55.785 --> 00:04:57.915
Total money supply in the economy.

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:00.810
Real world relevance.

00:05:01.229 --> 00:05:02.729
Why does all this matter?

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:06.900
Understanding money and banking
is absolutely vital to manage

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:10.229
customer finances properly
and follow all the rules.

00:05:10.650 --> 00:05:15.240
It directly impacts every decision
on lending, managing deposits, and

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:19.440
giving financial advice, making
sure the bank operates soundly.

00:05:19.830 --> 00:05:24.240
For customer financial management, this
knowledge helps a banker give the right

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:28.530
advice to customers based on their
specific needs and how much risk they

00:05:28.530 --> 00:05:31.200
can take for regulatory compliance.

00:05:31.350 --> 00:05:35.700
Understanding the rules ensures that
banks follow important guidelines like

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:38.340
KYC norms, anti-money laundering rules.

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:42.260
And fair lending practices
and for decision making.

00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:46.130
This knowledge is critical for
making smart decisions on interest

00:05:46.130 --> 00:05:50.300
rates, loan approvals, investment
strategies, and managing risks.

