00:07:17.465 --> 00:07:22.355
To remember the functions of money,
you can use a little trick F. It

00:07:22.355 --> 00:07:26.645
stands for facilitates exchange,
which is the medium of exchange.

00:07:27.034 --> 00:07:32.405
Intermediate store of value are store
of value, common measure of value, the

00:07:32.405 --> 00:07:36.724
unit of account and contractual payment,
the standard of deferred payment.

00:07:37.845 --> 00:07:42.885
Now for monetary aggregates, which measure
the money supply, they are ranked by

00:07:42.885 --> 00:07:45.615
liquidity from most liquid to least.

00:07:46.185 --> 00:07:50.775
M1 is the currency with the public
plus demand deposits with banks,

00:07:50.865 --> 00:07:56.625
plus other deposits with the RBIM
two is simply M1 plus the savings

00:07:56.625 --> 00:07:58.905
deposits of post office savings banks.

00:07:59.455 --> 00:08:05.155
M three, also known as broad money is
M1 plus the time deposits with banks.

00:08:05.545 --> 00:08:09.655
And M four is M three plus
the total deposits with post

00:08:09.655 --> 00:08:11.365
office savings organizations.

00:08:11.485 --> 00:08:13.675
But this excludes national
savings certificates.

00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:20.200
Let's look at the monetary policy
tools, the quantitative ones, CRR or

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:24.790
cash reserve ratio is the percentage
of net demand and time liabilities.

00:08:24.910 --> 00:08:31.390
NDTL that banks must keep with the
R-B-I-S-L-R or statutory liquidity ratio

00:08:31.510 --> 00:08:35.680
is the percentage of NDTL that banks
must maintain in liquid assets like.

00:08:36.370 --> 00:08:38.919
Cash gold or approved securities.

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:43.179
The repo rate is the rate at which
commercial banks borrow from the

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:47.080
RBI by selling securities with
an agreement to buy them back.

00:08:47.530 --> 00:08:49.720
The reverse repo rate is the opposite.

00:08:49.990 --> 00:08:53.260
It's the rate at which RBI
borrows from commercial banks.

00:08:53.675 --> 00:08:59.015
MSF or marginal standing facility is a
rate at which banks can borrow overnight

00:08:59.015 --> 00:09:04.025
from the RBI against securities, even
if they have used up their SLR quota.

00:09:04.475 --> 00:09:08.525
The bank rate is the rate at which
the RBI lends to commercial banks

00:09:08.525 --> 00:09:13.835
without any collateral and OMO or open
market operations is the buying and

00:09:13.835 --> 00:09:17.945
selling of government securities by
the RBI to control the money supply.

00:09:18.425 --> 00:09:21.215
Generally, there's a
relationship between these rates.

00:09:21.439 --> 00:09:25.730
The ban rate is usually higher than
the MSF rate, which is higher than

00:09:25.730 --> 00:09:29.240
the repo rate, which is in turn
higher than the reverse repo rate.

